<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1323,1193,1899]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
This subgenus includes two species originally described in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hogue and Denning 1983" authorityName="Hogue and Denning" authorityYear="1983" genus="Murielia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[972,1075,1193,1218]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Murielia</emphasis>
Hogue and 
<bibRefCitation author="Denning, D. G. &amp; Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L." pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="181 - 191" refId="ref21616" refString="Denning, D. G., Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L. (1983) New species of Phylloicus and a new Neotropical genus of Calamoceratidae (Trichoptera). Aquatic Insects, 5, 181 - 191." type="journal article" year="1983">Denning 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(in 
<bibRefCitation author="Denning, D. G. &amp; Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L." box="[374,618,1233,1259]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="181 - 191" refId="ref21616" refString="Denning, D. G., Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L. (1983) New species of Phylloicus and a new Neotropical genus of Calamoceratidae (Trichoptera). Aquatic Insects, 5, 181 - 191." type="journal article" year="1983">
Denning 
<emphasis box="[484,545,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
1983
</bibRefCitation>
). The genus was largely established to accommodate these two species, (described in the same paper), but the authors chose to select 
<taxonomicName authority="Flint (1968)" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1968" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Phylloicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="farri">
<emphasis box="[1137,1323,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Phylloicus farri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S., Jr." box="[264,404,1313,1339]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="151 - 153" refId="ref21696" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. (1968) New species of Trichoptera from the Antilles. The Florida Entomologist, 51, 151 - 153." type="journal article" year="1968">Flint (1968)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
as the 
<typeStatus box="[484,534,1313,1339]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
species for their new genus, based on what they believed to be synapomorphies. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S., Jr. &amp; Holzenthal, R. W. &amp; Harris, S. C." box="[552,772,1353,1379]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="73 - 84" refId="ref21987" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr., Holzenthal, R. W. &amp; Harris, S. C. (1999 b) Nomenclatural and systematic changes in the Neotropical caddisflies (Insecta: Trichoptera). Insecta Mundi, 13, 73 - 84." type="journal article" year="1999">
Flint 
<emphasis box="[614,673,1353,1378]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
(1999b)
</bibRefCitation>
recognized that the 
<typeStatus box="[1011,1061,1353,1379]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hogue and Denning" authorityYear="1983" box="[1193,1296,1353,1378]" genus="Murielia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1193,1296,1353,1378]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Murielia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a true species of 
<taxonomicName box="[484,608,1393,1418]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Phylloicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[484,608,1393,1418]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Phylloicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and therefore synonymized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hogue and Denning" authorityYear="1983" box="[964,1066,1393,1418]" genus="Murielia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[964,1066,1393,1418]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Murielia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName box="[1144,1268,1393,1418]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Phylloicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1144,1268,1393,1418]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Phylloicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He transferred the two new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hogue and Denning" authorityYear="1983" box="[680,783,1433,1458]" genus="Murielia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[680,783,1433,1458]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Murielia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Denning, D. G. &amp; Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L." box="[943,1190,1433,1459]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="181 - 191" refId="ref21616" refString="Denning, D. G., Resh, V. H. &amp; Hogue, C. L. (1983) New species of Phylloicus and a new Neotropical genus of Calamoceratidae (Trichoptera). Aquatic Insects, 5, 181 - 191." type="journal article" year="1983">Denning et al (1983)</bibRefCitation>
to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Banyallarga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the new species described in 
<emphasis box="[827,1222,1473,1498]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hogue and Denning" authorityYear="1983" box="[827,932,1473,1498]" genus="Murielia" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="genus">Murielia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[947,1222,1473,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutiterga">Banyallarga acutiterga</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortuna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B. fortuna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, along with a Venezuelan species, 
<taxonomicName box="[757,901,1513,1538]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mollicula">
<emphasis box="[757,901,1513,1538]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B. mollicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and several new species from Central America and northwestern South America do form a distinct clade within 
<taxonomicName box="[1177,1323,1553,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1177,1323,1553,1578]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Banyallarga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[273,360,1593,1619]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="73.[264,367,1824,1848]" captionTargetBox="[265,1303,318,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-24@73.[265,1304,312,1799]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURE 37. Relationships of calamoceratid genera (from Prather 2002)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028177/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
), whose distinctiveness was first recognized by Hogue and Denning. This clade is here described as a new subgenus of 
<taxonomicName box="[698,843,1633,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[698,843,1633,1658]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Banyallarga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1323,1193,1899]" lastBlockId="22.[264,1324,284,1310]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[312,475,1673,1698]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Histricoverpa">
<emphasis box="[312,475,1673,1698]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Histricoverpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from its sister subgenus by several characters. A pointed mesal process is present on the anterior margin of sternum VII (
<figureCitation box="[1119,1206,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="53.[264,367,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[267,1285,318,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-61@53.[267,1286,318,1755]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 16. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (UMSP00000051): abdominal segments IV–X, lateral view. FIGURE 17. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (A, D, E, holotype; B, C, UMSP000000056): A—lateral view; B—dorsal view; C—ventral view; D—phallus, lateral view; E—phallotremal sclerites, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028135" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028135/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), in some species also on sternum VI. The abdominal terga lack anteromesal notches. In males of several species (
<taxonomicName box="[460,613,1793,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutiterga">
<emphasis box="[460,478,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[494,613,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">acutiterga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[630,731,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="echinata">
<emphasis box="[630,731,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">echinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[748,834,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortuna">
<emphasis box="[748,834,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">fortuna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[850,900,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nica">
<emphasis box="[850,900,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">nica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[917,1033,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quincemil">
<emphasis box="[917,1033,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">quincemil</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[1101,1190,1793,1818]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvana">
<emphasis box="[1101,1190,1793,1818]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">sylvana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the single male specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[488,600,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[488,600,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[656,757,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanchezi">
<emphasis box="[656,757,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">sanchezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have lost segment IV) the lateral margin of sternum IV is deeply excavated (
<figureCitation box="[608,695,1873,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="53.[264,367,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[267,1285,318,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-61@53.[267,1286,318,1755]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 16. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (UMSP00000051): abdominal segments IV–X, lateral view. FIGURE 17. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (A, D, E, holotype; B, C, UMSP000000056): A—lateral view; B—dorsal view; C—ventral view; D—phallus, lateral view; E—phallotremal sclerites, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028135" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028135/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
); possibly this is related to the function of an abdominal glandular structure. In 
<emphasis box="[587,1264,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName box="[587,743,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutiterga">B. acutiterga</taxonomicName>
¸ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[759,863,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="echinata">echinata</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[876,965,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fortuna">fortuna</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[978,1031,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nica">nica</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[1045,1163,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quincemil">quincemil</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prather Table Of Contents" authorityYear="2004" box="[1176,1264,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sylvana">sylvana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blahnik &amp; Holzenthal" authorityYear="1992" box="[264,347,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tapanti">
<emphasis box="[264,347,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">tapanti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the posterolateral margin of segment IX is broadly produced as a rounded lobe (Fig. 17A). Generally, the preanal appendages are much longer than tergum X, except in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Calamoceratidae" genus="Banyallarga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mollicula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B. mollicula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and are somewhat flexible distally. The name refers to the thornlike setae on the phallic endothecal membrane (Figs. 17D, 21D), which are unique to the species in this subgenus. The endotheca was fully everted in only a few specimens, so I am unable to assess whether the arrangement of the thornlike setae is species­specific. In the female, the posterior end of the spermatheca is sclerotized as a sphere, with a posterior invagination where the spermathecal duct enters (
<figureCitation box="[692,801,604,630]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="56.[264,367,1350,1374]" captionTargetBox="[266,1322,327,1326]" captionTargetId="figure-45@56.[266,1322,326,1326]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 20. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) echinata. Female (BIOLAT/TRIC000000113): A— sterna IX, X and vaginal apparatus, ventral view; B—terga IX and X, dorsal view; C—sternum VIII, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028143/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Male. In some species, sternum IV lateral margin deeply excavated (
<figureCitation box="[1123,1211,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="53.[264,367,1765,1789]" captionTargetBox="[267,1285,318,1746]" captionTargetId="figure-61@53.[267,1286,318,1755]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 16. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (UMSP00000051): abdominal segments IV–X, lateral view. FIGURE 17. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Male (A, D, E, holotype; B, C, UMSP000000056): A—lateral view; B—dorsal view; C—ventral view; D—phallus, lateral view; E—phallotremal sclerites, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028135" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028135/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Tergum IX very short mesally; anterolateral margin of segment IX with broad rounded anterior process (Fig. 17A). Preanal appendages usually much longer than tergum X, narrow, several times longer than wide. Phallic endotheca bearing numerous thornlike setae or spines (Figs. 17D, 21D).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Female. Tergum IX with anterior marginal ridge entire, mesal ridge sometimes present. Sternum IX with anterior and posterior pair of striate lobes lateral to vaginal opening. Tergum X bearing paired posterolateral appendages, varying in shape, not extending 1/2 length beyond posterior margin of tergum; posteromesal portion of tergite membranous or semisclerotized. Sternum X mostly membranous except for bases of dorsal appendages; semisclerotized patches and short fine setae may be present lateral to anal opening. Vaginal apparatus complex (
<figureCitation box="[709,829,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="54.[264,367,1237,1261]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,326,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-46@54.[263,1323,326,1213]" captionTargetPageId="54" captionText="FIGURE 18. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) acutiterga. Female (UMSP000000051): A—sterna IX, X and vaginal apparatus, ventral view; B—terga IX and X, dorsal view; C—sternum VIII, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028137/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs. 18A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[842,896,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="56.[264,367,1350,1374]" captionTargetBox="[266,1322,327,1326]" captionTargetId="figure-45@56.[266,1322,326,1326]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 20. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) echinata. Female (BIOLAT/TRIC000000113): A— sterna IX, X and vaginal apparatus, ventral view; B—terga IX and X, dorsal view; C—sternum VIII, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028143/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">20A</figureCitation>
); posterior end of spermatheca sclerotized as a sphere, with posterior invagination where spermathecal duct enters (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1319,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="56.[264,367,1350,1374]" captionTargetBox="[266,1322,327,1326]" captionTargetId="figure-45@56.[266,1322,326,1326]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="FIGURE 20. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) echinata. Female (BIOLAT/TRIC000000113): A— sterna IX, X and vaginal apparatus, ventral view; B—terga IX and X, dorsal view; C—sternum VIII, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028143/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Figs. 20A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[264,319,1164,1190]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="58.[264,367,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,326,1410]" captionTargetId="figure-44@58.[264,1323,326,1410]" captionTargetPageId="58" captionText="FIGURE 22. Banyallarga (Histricoverpa) fortuna. Female (UMSP000218872): A—sterna IX, X and vaginal apparatus, ventral view; B—terga IX and X, dorsal view; C—sternum VIII, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5028147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5028147/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">22A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Etymology. From 
<emphasis box="[534,628,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">histricis</emphasis>
, Latin, meaning &quot;porcupine&quot;, and 
<emphasis box="[1055,1122,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">verpa</emphasis>
, Latin, meaning &quot;penis,&quot; for the phallus of these species, the endotheca of which is covered with thornlike setae that resemble the quills of a porcupine.
</paragraph>
